European debt write-downs are inevitable.
Berkeley — "That was just the Greek crisis," "That was just the crisis of Greece and Ireland," people once thought, but now it's not possible to think that way anymore, because it's clearly become a crisis for the entire eurozone.
To deal with it is both easier and more difficult than usually expected.
The economic reasoning behind this crisis is quite simple.
Greece has fiscal problems.
The banking system in Ireland has problems.
The private debt market in Portugal has problems.
Spain has problems in all three of the above aspects.
Although the details vary, the conclusion is the same: these countries all have to undergo a painful process of spending cuts.
To offset the side effects of contractionary policies, the usual approach is to combine domestic spending cuts with currency depreciation.
Devaluation enhances export competitiveness, meaning using foreign demand to compensate for domestic demand.
However, these countries are all members of the eurozone and do not have independent currencies that can be devalued, so they can only substitute external devaluation with internal devaluation.
They must cut wages, pensions, and other costs to enhance export competitiveness and achieve the effect of expanding external demand.
In fact, these crisis countries have made a significant determination to tighten their belts.
However, there is one economic variable that did not change with the adjustment of other variables, that is, the debt of the public and private sectors.
The book value of the government's accumulated debt has not changed, and bank debt — except for some debt owed to junior creditors — has remained largely unchanged as well.
It is this simple fact that puts internal devaluation strategies in a self-contradictory position: the heavier the cut in wages and other costs, the greater the relative burden of accumulating debt.
The heavier the debt burden, the more public spending needs to be cut and taxes increased to meet the debt of the government and its defenders (such as banks).
This in turn requires more internal devaluation, further increasing the debt burden, leading to a vicious cycle that drags the economy into a depression.
Therefore, for an internal devaluation strategy to take effect, it is necessary to find ways to reduce the face value of debt.
Government debt must be restructured.
Bank debts must be converted into equity, and when banks are insolvent, their debts should be written off.
Mortgage debt must also be written down.
It's understandable that policymakers are unwilling to take this path.
The sanctity of contracts.
The government is worried about losing trust in the financial market.
If creditors are primarily foreign, especially foreign banks, write-offs will only burden other countries.
These concerns are not entirely unfounded, but one should not draw unreasonable conclusions from them.
The only options are internal devaluation or external devaluation.
The leaders of European countries must choose one of two options.
They unanimously ruled out the possibility of external depreciation.
But internal depreciation necessarily requires debt restructuring.
Denying this is both illogical and unreasonable.
Debt restructuring is straightforward and clear.
The government can issue a batch of bonds with a face value discounted by a certain percentage from the current debt face value.
Bondholders can choose between two options: either hold onto their bonds and redeem them at face value with a later maturity date and lower interest rate, or accept discounted bonds with a lower face value than the existing ones, which mature earlier and carry a higher interest rate.
This isn't any kind of cutting-edge technology; people have done this before.
But there are three prerequisites to succeed.
First, we must assure the bondholders of the safety of the new bonds.
Someone has to guarantee these bonds.
In the 1980s, when Latin America restructured its debt under the Brady Plan, the U.S. Treasury played the role of the "big brother guarantor."
Now, the International Monetary Fund and the German government can take on this responsibility.
Second, all countries must act in unison.
Otherwise, the restructuring of one country may raise expectations for other countries, leading to transmission effects.
Finally, banks that suffer losses due to debt restructuring must strengthen their balance sheets.
These banks need to undergo real stress tests, not the mere ceremonial ones conducted earlier this year.
If debt restructuring indicates capital inadequacy, a comprehensive equity conversion of the relevant bank's assets should be carried out.
If that is not enough, the government must step in to inject capital into the relevant banks.
This also requires concerted action by all countries.
Once the bank's balance sheet is stabilized, it may be possible to restructure mortgage debt, bank debt, and other private sector debts without destabilizing the entire financial system.
Now let's talk about the biggest challenge.
All of this requires resolute leadership.
German leaders must acknowledge that their country's banks have significant exposure to debt in peripheral eurozone countries, and the situation is critical.
They must convince the backroom bosses and voters that guaranteeing public funds for debt restructuring and bank recapitalization is a necessary condition for an internal devaluation strategy; since Germany urged other EU countries to adopt this strategy, it should bear the responsibility of guaranteeing without hesitation.
In short, European leaders, especially German leaders, need to make the consequences seem more severe—otherwise, they will face big troubles.
Because that's just the way it is.
